# Part 3: Regression-Based Business Insights & Model Interpretation

---

## Task 6: Compare Models

### Models Compared

| Model | Independent Variables |
| :--- | :--- |
| Simple Regression 1 | marketing_spend |
| Simple Regression 2 | footfall |
| Multiple Regression | marketing_spend, footfall, staff_count, holiday_flag |

### R-Squared Comparison

| Model | R-Squared |
| :--- | :---: |
| Simple Regression 1 | 0.1672 |
| Simple Regression 2 | 0.7363 |
| Multiple Regression | 0.7848 |

### Interpretation

* Simple Regression 1 explains 16.72% of sales variation.
* Simple Regression 2 explains 73.63% of sales variation.
* Multiple Regression explains 78.48% of sales variation.
* Multiple Regression has the highest explanatory power.

### Significant Variables

| Variable | Significant? |
| :--- | :---: |
| marketing_spend | Yes |
| footfall | Yes |
| staff_count | No |
| holiday_flag | No |

### Business Usefulness

| Model | Business Usefulness |
| :--- | :--- |
| Simple Regression 1 | Evaluates marketing effectiveness |
| Simple Regression 2 | Evaluates customer traffic impact |
| Multiple Regression | Evaluates multiple sales drivers simultaneously |

### Limitations

#### Simple Regression 1
* Uses only marketing spend.
* Ignores operational factors.
* Lower explanatory power.

#### Simple Regression 2
* Uses only footfall.
* Ignores marketing and staffing effects.

#### Multiple Regression
* Assumes linear relationships.
* Does not include all possible business factors.

### Model Ranking

| Rank | Model | Reason |
| :---: | :--- | :--- |
| 1 | Multiple Regression | Highest R-Squared and includes multiple predictors |
| 2 | Simple Regression 2 | Strong explanatory power |
| 3 | Simple Regression 1 | Lowest explanatory power |

### Conclusion

* Multiple Regression is the preferred model.
* Footfall is the strongest predictor of monthly sales.
* Marketing spend positively impacts sales.
* Staff count and holiday flag have positive effects but weaker statistical support.